                    <div class="a-column " id="a-col">
                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-153135 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-amnesia tag-memory des-amnesia des-memory" id="post-153135">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">The Day of Forgetting</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Daan Heerma Van Voss			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-05-28T22:35:02+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">May 28, 2014 6:35 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">May 28, 2014 6:35 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I was 25 when I lost my memory. It happened on Jan. 16, 2012. I woke up, not knowing where I was. I was lying in bed, sure, but whose bed was it? There was no one in the room, no sound that I recognized: I was alone
                                        with my body. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Of course, my relationship to my body was radically different than before. My body parts seemed to belong to someone else or, rather, to something else. The vague sense of identity that I possessed was confined to the
                                        knowledge of my name, but even that felt arbitrary &#x2014; a collection of random letters, crumbling. No words can accurately describe the feeling of losing your memory, your life. <span id="more-153135"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/29/opinion/0529PRIVATELIVES/0529PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject"
                                            role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/29/opinion/0529PRIVATELIVES/0529PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/29/opinion/0529PRIVATELIVES/0529PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg"
                                                    id="100000002907395" width="480" height="628" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="628">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sammy Harkham</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Underlying the loss of facts is a deeper problem: the loss of logic and causality. A person can function, ask questions, only when he recognizes a fundamental link between circumstances and time, past and present. The
                                        links between something happening to you, leading you to do or say something, which leads to someone else responding. No act is without an act leading up to it, no word is without a word that came before.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Without the sense of causality provided by memory, there is chaos. When I woke up, I had no grip on logic, and logic none on me. It was a profound not-knowing, and it was terrifying. I started hyperventilating. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What struck me has a name: Transient Global Amnesia. T.G.A., as it&#x2019;s referred to, is a neurological disorder. The name sounds definitive, but in fact, it&#x2019;s just a fancy way of saying: We don&#x2019;t know
                                        the cause, we know only what the symptoms are. Its most defining symptom is a near total disruption of short-term memory. In many cases, there is a temporary loss of long-term memory as well. But there is a bright
                                        side. T.G.A. lasts for approximately two to 20 hours, so it&#x2019;s a one-day thing. At the time, though, I didn&#x2019;t know this.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Two names popped into my mind: Daniel and Sophie. I didn&#x2019;t know where the names came from, or to whom they belonged. I stumbled across the room, opened a door, and discovered that I was alone in the apartment.
                                        (It was, in fact, my apartment.) I found an iPhone and, quite magically, I thought, knew how to work it. As it turns out, there was nothing magical about this: A characteristic of T.G.A. is that those afflicted
                                        with it can perform familiar tasks, even ones as difficult as driving a car. (But I wouldn&#x2019;t recommend that.)</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Occurrence of T.G.A. is rare, with at most 10 cases per 100,000 people. It is most likely to happen when you&#x2019;re between 40 and 80; the average age of a T.G.A. patient is 62 years old. But I have always been in
                                        the fast lane.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The phone. Scrolling, I somehow reached my phone book. Five Sophies &#x2014; that&#x2019;s another story &#x2014; and one Daniel. I sent this Daniel a text message, asking if he was the kind of person I could go to
                                        when life got difficult. (The exact words I used are unprintable here.) </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">His answer: &#x201C;?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My response: &#x201C;I don&#x2019;t know anything.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This Daniel immediately called me, claiming to be my best friend. There was something familiar in his voice. He volunteered to come over. I was in no shape to decline.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I recognized him as soon as I opened the door. Daniel in fact turned out to be my oldest friend. I began learning about my life. He told me that I was a writer, that I loved Randy Newman, and that I hated people. I
                                        started to calm down. I now understood that I had lost my memory, which was reassuring. Before, I wasn&#x2019;t even aware that something like a memory existed, let alone that it could belong to someone like myself.
                                        </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the course of the afternoon, friends, relatives and former lovers stopped by, telling me about what they thought were the elements of my life. Memories came back to me, one by one. But while I nodded at everything
                                        they said, I almost instantly forgot it. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The medical stage of this day is of lesser importance. By the time the doctors got a hold of me, the existential fear had dissolved. I had trouble remembering new information, but, well, so does my father. He&#x2019;s
                                        the one who took me to the hospital. For retired people everything can be a vacation. I was slid into machines and passed from one medical center to the next, while he read soccer magazines. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As I calmed down, all my memories found me again. (How can one ever be sure, though?) I learned that it had not been a stroke, and there were no signs of permanent damage. The doctors said that I was in great shape,
                                        to which I responded: You can&#x2019;t be serious, I am 25 and I just lost my memory. As I said before, the cause of a T.G.A. spell remains unknown, otherwise it wouldn&#x2019;t be diagnosed as T.G.A. (Doctors are
                                        legally allowed to make circular arguments, I learned.)</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">People often ask me: Aren&#x2019;t you afraid it will happen to you again? The chances of it happening to me again are small, and they have not increased by the fact that it happened to me the first time. Indeed, there
                                        were moments in this new mode of consciousness in which countless causes for daily stress and fear simply did not exist, moments when I felt enlightened. Former patients often remember their day in oblivion as being
                                        light and carefree, and they go on living their lives with a vague but everlasting sense of homesickness. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There is a scene in the movie version of &#x201C;The World According to Garp&#x201D; in which Garp and his wife see a plane crash into a house. He immediately knows this is the house he wants to buy. The chance of another
                                        plane crash in the same place is simply too small to comprehend, he argues, so he will be safe. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These are our options: certain fear or illusionary invulnerability. I don&#x2019;t have to tell you which life is more worth living.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That night, I was afraid to go to sleep. I drank too much. The next morning, I woke up with my memory, and a hangover.</p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.daanheermavanvoss.nl/">Daan Heerma Van Voss</a> is a Dutch novelist whose third book, &#x201C;De Vergeting,&#x201D; is about memory loss.</em></p>
                                    <footer class="story-footer">
                                        <div class="story-meta">
                                            <p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 06/01/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">SR</span><span itemprop="printPage">9</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the
                                                headline: The Day of Forgetting.</p>
                                        </div>
                                    </footer>
                                </div>
